Part 1: The idea of relationships between variables

Until now…

  • we looked at differences between groups
  • more specifically: means comparison tests (z-test, t-tests)
  • usual form: independent variable \(\rightarrow\) dependent variable

We controlled/manipulated the independent variable (e.g. extra lessons vs no extra lessons)…

… and observed how this affected the dependent variable (e.g. statistics grade)

But!

  • very often we work with observational data
  • these are data where we cannot exert some manipulation or control

In these cases, we simply look at the relationship between variables

Kinds of relationships

  • both variables on the ratio or interval scale: Pearson correlation
  • both variables on the ordinal scale (ranks): Spearman correlation
  • one variable on the ratio or interval scale and one dichotomous variable: point biserial correlation
  • two dichotomous variables: Phi-coefficient (but more next week on the Chi-square test)

Example

2 7.73 18.06

4 7.42 22.30

In a plot

Characteristics

Each relationship has:

  • a strength
  • a direction (positive, negative)
  • a form (linear, quadratic, etc.)

What now?

  • we want to go beyond “eyeballing”
  • we need a numerical measure of the correlation
  • we want to test whether correlations are “significantly different from 0”

Part 2: Pearson correlation

Characteristics

  • describes the linear relationship between two variables
  • indicates the strength of the relationship
  • indicates the direction of the relationship

The correlation coefficient ranges from -1.00 to +1.00.

The correlation coefficient

  • population notation: \(\rho\) (Greek letter “rho”)
  • sample notation: \(r\)
  • effect size: \(R^2\)
  • negative values of \(r \rightarrow\) negative relationship
  • positive values of \(r \rightarrow\) positive relationship
  • values to the extremes (approaching \(\pm 1.00\)) indicate stronger relationships
  • values around 0 indicate weak (or no) relationships

The correlation coefficient

  • two variables \(x\) and \(y\)
  • if \(x\) changes, how much does \(y\) change

If we know the change of \(x\), is there a predictable change in \(y\)?

Scatterplot

General logic

  • to some degree \(x\) and \(y\) vary together
  • to some degree \(x\) and \(y\) vary separately

\(r = \frac{covariance}{variability\ of\ y\ and\ x\ separately}\)

Covariance

For a population: \(\sigma_{xy} = \frac{\sum{(x-\mu_x)(y-\mu_y)}}{N}\)

For a sample: \(s_{xy} = \frac{\sum{(x-M_x)(y-M_y)}}{n-1}\)

Mini example

participant grade hours
1 5 17
2 8 18
3 5 17
4 7 22
5 6 22

Covariance step-by-step

  1. Means of the two variables

\(M_{grade} = 6.2\)

\(M_{hours} = 19.2\)

Covariance step-by-step

  1. Deviations
participant grade (\(x\)) hours (\(y\)) \(x-M_x\) \(y-M_y\)
1 5 17 -1.2 -2.2
2 8 18 1.8 -1.2
3 5 17 -1.2 -2.2
4 7 22 0.8 2.8
5 6 22 -0.2 2.8

Covariance step-by-step

  1. Product of deviations
participant grade (\(x\)) hours (\(y\)) \(x-M_x\) \(y-M_y\) \((x-M_x)(y-M_y)\)
1 5 17 -1.2 -2.2 2.64
2 8 18 1.8 -1.2 -2.16
3 5 17 -1.2 -2.2 2.64
4 7 22 0.8 2.8 2.24
5 6 22 -0.2 2.8 -0.56

Covariance step-by-step

  1. Obtaining the sum of products of deviations

This is \(\sum{(x-M_x)(y-M_y)}\).

In the book (page 490), this is called SP

We obtain:

\(\sum{(x-M_x)(y-M_y)} = 2.64+(-2.16)+2.64+2.24+(-0.56) = 4.8\)

Covariance step-by-step

  1. Dividing by \(N\) (population) or \(n-1\) (sample)

We have a sample of \(n=5\), so:

\(s_{xy} = \frac{\sum{(x-M_x)(y-M_y)}}{n-1} = \frac{4.8}{4} = 1.2\)

The covariance between \(x\) (grade) and \(y\) (hours) is 1.2.

But this is depending on the data’s scale - don’t we have a corrected version of this covariability value?

From covariance to correlation

We need to correct this covariance to obtain a dimensionless metric.

This correction happens via the standard deviations:

\(s_{grade} = SD_{grade} = 1.30\)

\(s_{hours} = SD_{hours} = 2.59\)

\(r=\frac{s_{xy}}{s_x*s_y} = \frac{1.20}{1.30*2.59} = \frac{1.20}{3.37} = 0.36\)

The correlation coefficient \(r\) indicates a positive relationship between the grade and the learning hours, \(r=0.36\).

An alternative way

In the book, the formula is used as follows:

\(r=\frac{SP}{\sqrt{SS_x*SS_y}}\)

\(SS_x = 6.8\) (grade)

\(SS_y = 26.8\) (hours)

So: \(r=\frac{SP}{\sqrt{SS_x*SS_y}}=\frac{4.8}{\sqrt{6.8*26.8}} = \frac{4.8}{13.59} = 0.36\)

Identical result but different formula.

An effect size for \(r\)

There is a simple way of expressing the absolute magnitude of the effect:

we just square \(r\) and obtain \(R^2\) (or \(r^2\))

Here: \(R^2 = 0.36^2 = 0.13\)

13% of the variance of the grade can be explained by (predicted with) from the no. of hours learned (and vice versa!!)

Where is it useful?

Correlation solves a lot of problems:

  • core of predictive modeling (regression and also in AI eventually)
  • testing of ideas (do people in extremist communities have a lower IQ?)
  • assessing re-test reliability (e.g. testing your typing speed twice)

Pitfall

This is one of the main pitfalls in almost all of research!!

Correlation does not imply causation

Always remember that.

The ice cream and crime example.

Part 3: Hypothesis testing with the Pearson correlation

Correlation and hypotheses

We can test whether a correlation is significant.

Significant means here: significantly different from 0.

Our two hypotheses then are:

  • \(H_0: \rho=0\)
  • \(H_1: \rho \neq 0\) (two-sided)
  • \(H_1: \rho>0\)(one-sided)
  • \(H_1: \rho<0\)(one-sided)

Testing \(r\)

We test our hypothesis using the known structure via the t-statistic.

\(t=\frac{sample\ value - population\ value}{standard\ error}\)

We know that:

  • sample value = calculated (observed) \(r\)
  • population value = \(\rho\) (as per \(H_0\))

What about the SE?

The standard error

\(s_r = \sqrt{\frac{1-r^2}{n-2}}\)

So that:

\(t = \frac{r-\rho}{s_r}\)

Our example

We had: \(r=0.36\) for \(n=5\)

\(s_r = \sqrt{\frac{1-r^2}{n-2}}=\sqrt{\frac{1-0.36^2}{5-2}}=\sqrt{\frac{0.87}{3}} = 0.54\)

\(t = \frac{r-\rho}{s_r}=\frac{0.36-0}{0.54} = 0.67\)

The critical t-value was for \(df=n-2 = 3\) –> 3.182 (two-tailed for \(\alpha = .05\))

So we cannot reject the null hypothesis. The correlation is not significantly larger than 0.

Another example

Testing the hypotheses

  • we have data from \(n=1200\) students and their learning hours and statistics grade
  • we use an \(\alpha=.01\) for the hypothesis that more learning hours lead to a higher grade

\(H_0: \rho=0\) and \(H_1: \rho>0\)

Calculating \(r\) results in \(r=0.60\)

Obtaining \(t\)

\(s_r = \sqrt{\frac{1-r^2}{n-2}}=\sqrt{\frac{1-0.60^2}{1200-2}}=\sqrt{\frac{0.64}{1198}} = 0.0001\)

\(t = \frac{r-\rho}{s_r}=\frac{0.60-0}{0.0001} = 6000\)

This t-value is far more extreme than the critical t-value (\(t=2.326\)), so we reject \(H_0\).

In the live session

  • correlation mini example by hand
  • live study on real-world correlations

Recap

  • often we want to assess the relationship between two variables
  • this implies we cannot use any manipulation or control
  • instead, we measure the correlation between these variables
  • the Pearson correlation coefficient indicates the strength and direction of a linear relationship

If you want to “guess” correlations, here’s a game: http://guessthecorrelation.com/
